post_text:
Maconaquah Students Participate in Cross-Curricular STEM Project

This week, Maconaquah’s eighth grade class had the opportunity to learn about different types of Native American dwellings. The group started their adventure in Social Studies class where they studied the different dwelling types and then picked which dwelling they would build to scale. Students then learned how to scale in mathematics, allowing them the knowledge to build their model appropriately. Students utilized the Engineering Design Process they learned in Science class to build their models. Finally, in English/Language Arts class, students read about different types of Native American dwellings, and had a discussion about them in class. “This was a great way for our teachers to educate students on how the different subject areas can work together to create one final project,” said Social Studies teacher Michael Sommers. “It was an added bonus that the students loved it!”

Thanks and GO BRAVES!!!

6th Grade Students:

Welcome sixth grade students. We are excited to start the 2020-2021 school year. Please use the link below to view the 2020-2021 introductory video. The video should answer questions about room locations and expectations for parents and students. We will have a 6th grade/new student walk through on July 28 from 5PM to 7PM. As a reminder, students will not be assigned lockers so it should make the walk through easier for our 6th grade students. Please follow the bullet points below to help stop the spread.

- Maintain social distancing during your visit(6 feet apart)
- Use entrance 1S only(Schedules will be handed out in the office)
- Everyone must wear a face covering over their mouth nose while in the building
- 1 student and 1 adult may enter per family
- Last names A through L attend between 5 and 6/Last names M through Z attend between 6 and 7

Link to Orientation Video- https://drive.google.com/file/d/1P9XSX8dFnwzcB70GhzP26WZXTyHczQ1P/view

Please feel free to contact me if you have any questions. We are looking forward to seeing you July 28!

Good afternoon, Braves! Online Registration for all returning and new Maconaquah students opens Wednesday, July 15th @ 9 am! We encourage all families of returning and new students to complete registration online from the comfort of your home. Please access the online registration from the school corporation website under the Parents tab and choose Registration.

If you are having Skyward technical issues with registering, contact the Technology Center at 765-689-9131 x5999. It is best to register using a computer not a phone or tablet.

Starting July 20th, if you do not have access to the internet at home, one parent may come into the school and register from 9 am - 3 pm. We will have laptops set up for you to complete the registration process. We will be practicing social distancing and we require facial coverings to be worn.

All school supply lists and school-specific details are listed on the Registration page.

We are looking forward to another great school year!

post_text:
Maconaquah Patrons,

We want to say thank you for all of the feedback we've received over our plans for returning to school. We had a great turnout at our public forum, and there were so many great questions that were asked. Our COVID-19 Back to School Guidelines have been approved by the School Board, and the official copy can be found on our corporation web page (https://www.maconaquah.k12.in.us/). The FAQ page has been updated to list new questions asked by parents and members of our community. Please do not hesitate to ask questions as they arise. Prior to the start of school, we will be sending out guidance over proper ways to wear face coverings, and signs and symptoms of COVID-19, so please be looking for that. We appreciate all of the support, and look forward to seeing our students on August 3rd.

Go Braves!

text:
Maconaquah Patrons,

We want to say thank you for all of the feedback we've received over our plans for returning to school. We had a great turnout at our public forum, and there were so many great questions that were asked. Our COVID-19 Back to School Guidelines have been approved by the School Board, and the official copy can be found on our corporation web page (https://www.maconaquah.k12.in.us/). The FAQ page has been updated to list new questions asked by parents and members of our community. Please do not hesitate to ask questions as they arise. Prior to the start of school, we will be sending out guidance over proper ways to wear face coverings, and signs and symptoms of COVID-19, so please be looking for that. We appreciate all of the support, and look forward to seeing our students on August 3rd.

Go Braves!

July 1, 2020

Attention Maconaquah Patrons,

Maconaquah’s Back to School Task Force has finished the initial COVID-19 Back to School Guidelines. The guidelines can be found at https://www.maconaquah.k12.in.us/updates. It is very important to inform our patrons that the COVID-19 Back to School Guidelines HAVE NOT been School Board approved. This is a fluid, changing document, and is being sent out to our patrons to allow time for questions to be asked prior to final approval. Maconaquah School Corporation will be holding a public work session on July 6th at 6PM in the high school auditorium to further explain this document and to answer any questions that have not already been answered within this document. There have been changes made since our first release to the public, so please read through these guidelines carefully to note those minor changes.

Thank you for your support as we work towards getting our students back to school for the 2020-21 school year.

This week, Maconaquah High School was informed that one of their very own would receive a Platinum award from the 2020 National French Contest.

A Platinum winner is the highest award in the Le Grand Concours. Junior Anastasia Spahr earned the top score in the nation in her division. The award includes a platinum medal, a plaque, and a Lauréat national certificate.

Way to go Anastasia!

May 1, 2020

Parents, Students, and Staff,

With the Governors new guidance, all buildings and campus grounds will remain closed until July 4th at the earliest. This means no students on campus grounds (outside of the item pick-up dates below). Teachers will continue generating online work for students to complete Tuesdays, Wednesdays, and Thursdays. For those students who do not have access to online content, please contact your building principal.

We have decided to push back student item pick-up to the week of May 25th. This will also give students the chance to have completed all school work for the 2020 school year, allowing students and parents to ask any pertinent questions prior to pick-up times. Each building will have their own guidance for pick-up, with those specifics to come in the next few weeks.

At this time, we will continue to provide food service to Bunker Hill United Methodist Church and Helping Hands.

post_text:
Maconaquah High School received notice this week that one of their very own was selected as French Teacher of the Year for the state of Indiana. Viviane Tripp, President of the American Association of Teachers of French Indiana Chapter, and Blandine Baldwin, President of the AATF Northwest Chapter contacted Marcet Spahr this week to let her know the exciting news. “It is nice to have some good news in these unsettling times!” said Spahr.

Marcet will be recognized at the Indiana Foreign Language Teachers Association annual conference this fall. “We couldn’t be more proud,” said Maconaquah Superintendent Doctor James Callane. “We know how hard our staff work, especially during this time away from students, but it is very refreshing to see others recognize the hard work and accomplishments of teachers like Marcet who have a true passion for what they do. Congratulations to Mrs. Spahr, and thank you for all you do for our Maconaquah Braves!”

post_text:
April 8, 2020

Maconaquah Families,

We wanted to make you aware that we received information this afternoon that one of our employees has tested positive for COVID-19. This individual was one of the volunteers helping with Maconaquah’s Food Service Day on April 2nd. This individual helped pack lunches, however, she did not distribute food in the pick-up line. If you have any questions regarding COVID-19, please contact the Miami County Health Department at 765-472-3901. At this time, we will continue to provide food service to the three agencies previously mentioned (Bunker Hill United Methodist Church, Amboy Christian Church, and Helping Hands). We will continue to update you with any new information as it comes.

Stay safe Braves,

Dr. Callane

post_text:
Hey Future Kindergarten Parents! We will be postponing our Kindergarten Round Up. However, you should still register your child online within the next 2 weeks. This is a VERY important step. This will give us your contact information so that we can alert you to changes moving forward. This will also allow us to send you a postcard letting you know when your child can meet his/her new teacher in July!

PLEASE COMPLETE YOUR REGISTRATION TODAY! School staff will be in and out of the building beginning Friday, April 3rd. You may leave a message with any questions with our school secretary, Mrs. Kaufman. She will return your call the next time she is in. PLEASE DO NOT COME TO THE SCHOOL.

Please be aware that we had new phones installed over Spring Break, so there may be a few kinks in the new system.
We wish you and your loved ones health and well-being in the coming weeks!

post_text: We were the Maconaquah “Superhero Spellers” at the Peru Rotary Club Spell-a-thon competition tonight at Blair Pointe Elementary School. Our team won the “Most Spirited” Award this evening which was voted on by the other teams that were competing. Members of the team included: Breanna Manriquez, Jenny Walsh, Brandi Bowman, and Jennifer Lorona. A special thank you goes out to Dr. Callane for allowing us to participate and Mrs. McPike for the superhero capes and masks.

At the meeting, all questions will be answered and there will be discussions over some of the league rules and fees. Come join one of Americas fastest and safest high school sports, and be part of the first Clay Shooting Team in Miami county.

post_text:
Way to go, Braves!

2nd Grade: Sophia Corn
Sophia has come a long way. She used to say, "I can't" before she would even try. Now, she does whatever she can to work through the new skills that she has learned this year. She works hard and has good focus. Sophia's smile is contagious and I love ending my day with her in math class.

3rd Grade: Marabelle Yeung
I love having Marabelle in Art class! She always has a great attitude and is a hard worker. On Elearning days she always does her assignments and will always do extra work. She is such a joy to have in class!

4th Grade: Camille Kellems
Camille is a great student to have in class. She always tries her best and is a really good friend to all of her classmates. She is also a great listener and follows directions quickly.

5th Grade: Braydon Wiggs
Braydon comes to class with a smile on his face. He always has a good attitude and does his best on his work. He has a fun humorous personality that brings excitement to our class. I am really happy to have him in my class and to have been able to get to know him.

March 3 - Superhero Day at Mac El! In conjunction with National School Breakfast Week and our Superhero Family Night, we will have a school spirit day on Tuesday! Students may dress as their favorite superhero either real superheroes such as police officers, firefighters, astronauts or make believe superheroes such as Batman, Superman, etc. Please make sure your spirit wear is school appropriate and no masks covering your face!
Join us for Family Night and Celebrate Our Superheroes!

March 3, 2020, 5:30-7:00
Join us for food, fun, and a chance to meet our superheroes!
Students must be accompanied by an adult!

post_text:
Congrats to this weeks Braves of the Week!

2nd Grade: Dax Mooney
Dax is a great example of a BRAVE!
He is kind and respectful of students and staff. He works hard and always tries to do his best. He’s a leader and a good role model for the rest of the class.
3rd Grade: Ciena Alvarez
Ciena is a great student. She comes to school every day with a smile on her face. She is kind and helpful to her classmates. She works very hard on her school work. Ciena is a joy to have in class.
4th Grade: Nevaah Moore
Nevaah has demonstrated what it means to be a BRAVE in my classroom. She is always asking how she can help me. Recently when a new student started in my classroom, Nevaah was the first one to make her feel welcome. Keep up the good work, Nevaah!
5th Grade: Lexi Ploor
Lexi is respectful, kind, and hardworking. She comes in every day with a great attitude, and has a genuine love of learning. She gives 100% at whatever it is she is working on. She always has a smile on her face and asks how my day has gone so far. It has been great to see her grow in the last couple of years!
